{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_bowtruckle_ver02/data/sn85040749/0027176909A/1921010601/0003.xml":{"full_text":"OPEN SHOP NEWS\nWhat Will 1921 Bring to America!\n\nCONSIDER THE FOLLOWING FACTS:\nAlthough the United States of America has only 6% of the\nworld\u2019s population and only 7 of the world\u2019s land,\nYET WE PRODUCE\n20 X of the world\u2019s supply of gold; 60 of the world\u2019s supply of aluminum\n25 wheat; 60 X copper;\n40 X iron and steel; 60 cotton;\n40% lead; 66% oil;\n40% silver; 75 corn;\n50% zinz; 85* automobiles;\n52 X coal; (The list might be continued indefinitely)\nOur country has the resources and the Our country\u2019s surplus is needed by the\nability to produce an enormous share of the want and poverty of Europe and Asia,\ngoods and commodities that the world needs. How bring them together\nThe country has the capital, the labor America\u2019s leading financiers have\nand the managing ability to supply not only worked put a $100,000,000 corporation to\nits own needs but a large part of the needs engage in international trade which should\nof the rest of the world. he able to solve the problem of how to get\n!vt i*i i our goods and our food to these starving\nMo country prospers m which each man s\nonly produces enough tor his own needs.\nThe American farmer produces more per La As soon as that is solved industry will\nman than any farmer on earth; so does the thriv agai al *\u00b0ugh everything will be\nx itl j on a. lower basis ot money compensation.\nAmerican laboring man under competent r\nmanaapniput All industry will thrive again, then,\n_ g i a j. c unless strikes and discord and false labor\ni-Airope and Asia are in dire need ol leadership and unfair management upset\nfood and manufactured goods. For want the well grounded hope of a peaceful year\nof food millions will suffer and may die. in business, industry and commerce.\nThat peace car. best be maintained where employer and\nemployee both recognize the justice of the OPEN SHOP.\nTHE \u201cWAUSAU\u201d POLICY:\n1. EMPLOY workingmen and women without any regard\nwhatsoever to the fact that they do or do not belong to\nany labor organizations.\ni\n2. BASE the pay of such employees upon their individual\nskill, ability and industry.\n3. PAY employes as high wages as existing conditions will\npermit.\n4. MAINTAIN reasonable working hours and the best work\ning conditions possible, consistent with the line of industry.\n5. EXPECT from each employee an honest day\u2019s work, per\nformed to the best of his ability.\n6. PROTECT every man and woman in the lawful exercise\nof his or her natural right to earn a livelihood.\n7. RECOGNIZE the right of employees to submit any and\nall complaints and wage questions to their employers,\neither individually, collectively, or by committee from\ntheir number.\n8. DENY the right of outside parties to interfere in matters\narising between employee and employer.\n9. DEM AND that there be Justice and the Square Deal for\nall, and License and Special Privilege for none.\n10. INDORSE and support every organization, whether of\nEmployers, Employees or the General Public standing\nfor Law and Order and for the rights of American Citi\nzens.\nTHE WAUSAU PILOT\nSome of the WAUSAU EMPLOYERS\nwho have endorsed the \u201cWAUSAU\nPOLICY\nBROOKS ROSS LUMBER CO.\nBUILDERS LUMBER AND SUPPLY CO.\nCEREAL MILLS CO.\nCURTIS YALE CO.\nDANIELSON TOOL CO.\nDODGE-HOOKER MILLS\nGOODWILLIE BROS.\nB. HEINEMANN LUMBER CO.\nHEINEMAN-GORMAN LUMBER CO.\nJACOB MORTENSON LUMBER CO.\nJ. M. KUEBLER CO.\nJOHNSON ELECTRIC CO.\nMARATHON ELECTRIC MFG. CO.\nMARATHON PAPER MILLS CO.\nMARATHON MOTOR CO.\nMENASHA PRINTING AND CARTON CO.\nD. J. MURRAY MANUFACTURING CO.\nMORGAN BROS.\nNO T,rr \u201dF'i?\\ MILLING CO.\nJ. MORTENSON LUMBER CO. (Retail Dept.)\nW. H. NABLO\nNORTHWESTERN DYEING CLEANING WORKS\nPETH CANDY CO.\nPIER LUMBER CO.\nQUANDT\u2014SMITH ELECTRIC CO.\nSTELTZ\u2014ZIEGLER ELECTRIC CO.\nUNDERWOOD VENEER CO.\nUNION TANNING CO.\nWAUSAU ABRASIVES CO.\nWAUSAU BOX LUMBER CO.\nWAUSAU CANNING CO.\nWAUSAU EXCELSIOR CO.\nWAUSAU FOUNDRY AND MACHINE CO.\nWAUSAU IRON WORKS CO.\nWAUSAU LAND CO.\nWAUSAU LAUNDRY CO.\nWAUSAU LUMBER CO.\nWAUSAU MASTER BUILDER S\u2019 ASS\u2019N.\nWAUSAU MFG. CO.\nWAUSAU MOTOR CAR CO.\nWAUSAU NOVELTY CO.\nWAUSAU QUARTZ CO.\nWAUSAU TELEPHONE CO.\nWAUSAU PAPER MILLS CO.\nWISCONSIN AUTO SUPPLY CO.\nWISCONSIN BOX CO.\nWISCONSIN BOX CO. Retail Dept.)\nWISCONSIN RIVER SUPPLY CO.\nWISCONSIN ENGINEERING\nAND CONSTRUCTION CO\nWISCONSIN PACKING CO.\nWISCONSIN VALLEY ELECTRIC CO.\nYAWKEY-BISSELL LUMBER CO.\nLiIDATIJ END\nIS NOW IN SIGHT\nStress on Business Now Passed,\nSay Financial Experts.\nFEW SORE SPOTS IN SIGHT\nLeading Financiers Have Confidence\nin the Year to Follow\u2014Admit De\nflation in Commodities Has\nBeen Severe.\nNew York, Jan. I.\u2014The financial\nand business stress of the past few\nmonths is definitely passed. There are\nstill a good many sore spots, but they\nme being gradually cured and the out\nlook for 1021 Indicates that a sounder\nand more normal business condition\nlias been attained.\nDeflation in commodities has been a\nsevere task to many merchants who\nloaded up at high prices, hilt the cure\nis well on its way and resulting in a\nhealthier business condition during the\ncoming year.\nGary an Optimist.\nThese are (conclusions readied on a\ngeneral inquiry made of financial and\nbusiness lenders throughout the United\nStates and may be epitomized in the\nfollowing expressions:\nElbert M. (Jury, chairman of the\nboard of directors of the United States\nSteel corporation: \u2018\u2018l am as hopeful\nand confident of the future I have been\nat any time. Conditions are no worse\nthan many months ago. The wonder\nis that they have not been much worse.\nConditions are abnormal and even the\nminds of thoughtful people tire dis\ntorted. This, of course, Is a result of\nthe terrible time we have just passed\nthrough. 1 wish to refer particularly\n!to the United States and our own situ\nation \u2014our opportunities and prospects.\n1 have before referred to the particu\nlar resources of the country. Others\nhave frequently done this and the\nnewspapers have published facts and\nfigures. In addition to these we have\nthe spirit and determination to over\ncome all obstacles to the greatest sue.\ncess.\u201d\nTurn of Tide Near.\nCharles H. Sabin, president of the\nGuaranty Trust company: \u201cThose\nwho are most closely studying the ex\nisting situation feel that the turn of\ntlie tide in declining prices and liquida\ntion is very near. Although there are\nmany readjustments from the effects\nof war yet to lie made in the months\nand years to come they believe there\nIs reasonable assurance of a return to\nnormal business conditions, stabilized\nprices, easier money and larger busi\nness opportunities. It should he ii\nsource of particular congratulation to\n(lie people iliat American financial in\nstitutions, on tlic whole, arc on a sound\nbasis and amply prepared to meet\nboth tin* problems the .situation raises\nand tlie opportunities that are certain\nto follow.\u201d\nDaniil Guggenheim: \u201cThe West has\na great fundamental faith in .Vmerica's\nfuture. Although there Is considerable\nunemployment, 1 hove found that ii is\nchiefly among the roving class. The\ngood, steady, married American is\nholding Ills job and lias saved money.\u201d\nI\u2019uul M. Warburg, former chairman\nfederal reserve hoard: \"If actual\n'peace is established in Europe, if the\nobligations of a surviving and recuper\nating Germany will prove an asset of\nvalue in the balance sheet of her con\nquerors and if, at tin* same time, po\nlitical and social order in Germany\nwill exert its healing Influence In ltus\nsla, the lowest point will have been\nreadied, and all the world will soon\ntie on tin- uphill grade. That will hi*\nthe moment when we may throw our\n.weight Into the scales and tip them\nfrom despondency to courage and\ni cheer. It Is then Mint the ambitious\nplans of relief may come Into full frui\ntion and that the world deadlock in\nproduction and trade may be broken.\u201d\nWages Must Come Down.\nJ. A. Stillman, president National\nCity bank, New York \u201cThe existing\nstate of business depression over the\nworld Is the natural result of the low\npurchasing power of the population of\nEurope as affected by their disorgan\nized Industries. European production\nmust be revived and industries of the\nworld brought buck Into balance be\nfore astute of general prosperity can\nhe re-established. Prices which have\nfallen to approximately prewar levels\nmay he presumed to he lower than\nthey are likely to remain permanently\nbut prices which are still bused upon\ninflated costs, including wages at dou\nble prewar rates, are quite certain to\ncome down.\u201d\nTWO DIE IN C. E. I. WRECK\nFast Passenger Train Derailed at\nYard's Center, Eighteen Miles\nFrom Chicago.\nChicago, Jan. I.\u2014The fireman vns\nkilled and the engineer was fatally\nInjured when th-> St. Louis limited\ntrain on the Chicago Eastern Illi\nnois railroad was wrecked at Yard's\nCenter, 111., 18 miles from Chicago.\nThe train was southbound and was\ngoing 50 miles an hour. The dead:\nG, Gilly, fireman. Thrown 50 feet\nfrom the engine.\nCharles Stoner,' engineer. Died in\nSt. Bernard's hospital, Chicago.\nScores of passengers In the four\ncoaches were shaken up, but none\nwriously Injured, ft was said.","height":"28417","width":"19730"}}
